**Attribute filters on `SearchFilter` (0.8.20 Slice 15e, R-20-PR / ADR-0.8.11 D3).**
`SearchFilter` gains a public field `attributes: Vec<(String, String)>` — each
`(attribute_name, value)` is an equality predicate over a declared-`filterable`
projection, lowered pre-KNN into the indexed vec0 metadata column `attr_<hex>`
(never a post-KNN `json_extract`). Empty ⇒ the byte-identical unfiltered path is
preserved. The struct is now `#[non_exhaustive]`, so EXTERNAL crates must
construct it through `..Default::default()` (a further additive field is then not
a source break). Allowlist MEMBERSHIP in
`src/conformance/governed-surface-allowlist.json` is byte-unchanged (`SearchFilter`
was already a re-exported type; this is a fields-only + attribute delta, the same
pattern as `PreparedWrite::Node`'s validity fields). Semantics are **node-scoped**:
an attribute filter EXCLUDES every edge hit on both retrieval arms (edges are never
attribute-projected), which is HITL ruling (A) — `(A)` is `(D)` endpoint-node
filtering with an empty endpoint rule; (B)/(C)/(D) are reserved widenings, none

codex
The patch has API-visible correctness issues in projection/filter handling: undeclared attribute filters can produce raw SQL failures, and some accepted projection changes are reported as unchanged. These should be fixed before treating the patch as correct.

Full review comments:

- [P2] Reject filters for undeclared attributes before SQL — /home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/orch-0.8.20-s15b/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:9901-9902
  When `SearchFilter.attributes` contains a name that is not currently declared `filterable` (or the live `vector_default` shape has not got that `attr_<hex>` column), this emits `AND attr_<hex>=?...` directly into the vec0 KNN query. SQLite then fails with `no such column`, so a caller typo or missing `configure_projections` turns into a storage/search failure instead of a stable invalid-filter/no-match outcome, and the text arm behaves differently because it just probes `canonical_attributes`.

- [P2] Report deferred-only registry mutations — /home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/orch-0.8.20-s15b/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:16148-16149
  If a projection is already deferred and the caller adds another deferred-only target without any EAV build, such as changing `rankable` to `rankable + vector`, this condition suppresses `delta.deferred`; the request persists a different registry row but `delta` remains empty and `unchanged` is set to true. That makes an accepted registry mutation look like an idempotent no-op to SDK callers.
The patch has API-visible correctness issues in projection/filter handling: undeclared attribute filters can produce raw SQL failures, and some accepted projection changes are reported as unchanged. These should be fixed before treating the patch as correct.

Full review comments:

- [P2] Reject filters for undeclared attributes before SQL — /home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/orch-0.8.20-s15b/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:9901-9902
  When `SearchFilter.attributes` contains a name that is not currently declared `filterable` (or the live `vector_default` shape has not got that `attr_<hex>` column), this emits `AND attr_<hex>=?...` directly into the vec0 KNN query. SQLite then fails with `no such column`, so a caller typo or missing `configure_projections` turns into a storage/search failure instead of a stable invalid-filter/no-match outcome, and the text arm behaves differently because it just probes `canonical_attributes`.

- [P2] Report deferred-only registry mutations — /home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/orch-0.8.20-s15b/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:16148-16149
  If a projection is already deferred and the caller adds another deferred-only target without any EAV build, such as changing `rankable` to `rankable + vector`, this condition suppresses `delta.deferred`; the request persists a different registry row but `delta` remains empty and `unchanged` is set to true. That makes an accepted registry mutation look like an idempotent no-op to SDK callers.
